beaches.name: Potlatch State Park
beaches.notes: Excellent oyster beach. Best digging in middle intertidal zone in sand/gravel.

beaches.name: Dosewallips State Park
beaches.notes: Excellent for oysters year-round. Southern portion permanently closed - check map. Clams closed in 2025-2026 for recovery.

beaches.name: Twanoh State Park
beaches.notes: Excellent oyster beach. Best oyster spot near boat ramp. Clams in narrow band below oyster beds. Open year-round for oysters.

beaches.name: Belfair State Park
beaches.notes: Excellent for oysters and Manila clams. Parts of beach very muddy - look for firmer substrate. Enhanced oyster beds.

beaches.name: Lilliwaup State Park
beaches.notes: Excellent oyster beach. Beach is mostly rocky - digging is difficult.

beaches.name: Eagle Creek
beaches.notes: Good for oysters. Near freshwater creek influence.

beaches.name: Scenic Beach State Park
beaches.notes: CLOSED for conservation since 2010 due to oyster bed damage. Check for reopening status.

beaches.name: Port Gamble
beaches.notes: Historic mill town with good shellfish access. Check current closure status.

beaches.name: DNR-68 (Point No Point)
beaches.notes: DNR public beach. Good variety of clam species.

beaches.name: DNR-69
beaches.notes: DNR public beach near Point No Point.

beaches.name: Penrose Point State Park
beaches.notes: Good variety of clams and oysters. Scenic location on Mayo Cove.

beaches.name: Kopachuck State Park
beaches.notes: Good clam beach. Beach has mix of sand and gravel substrate.

beaches.name: Dash Point State Park
beaches.notes: Urban beach with moderate clam populations. Good for beginners.

beaches.name: Camano Island State Park
beaches.notes: Good variety on Saratoga Passage. Nice family beach.

beaches.name: Birch Bay State Park
beaches.notes: Popular north sound beach. Large tide flats for easy clamming. Good horse clams in sandy areas.

beaches.name: Sequim Bay State Park
beaches.notes: Protected bay with good shellfish variety. Calm waters. Sandy substrate good for horse clams.

beaches.name: Dungeness Recreation Area
beaches.notes: Large tide flats. Wildlife refuge - some areas restricted.

beaches.name: Mystery Bay State Park
beaches.notes: Historic Chemakum tribe clamming site. Oysters seeded by WDFW near boat ramp. Fire rings available.

beaches.name: Fort Flagler State Park
beaches.notes: GEODUCK beach! Best butter clams between mainland and Rat Island. Geoduck in sandy Kilisut Harbor side at -2ft tide.

beaches.name: Fort Worden State Park
beaches.notes: WARNING: Western beach permanently closed - shellfish not safe. Seaweed harvest April 16-May 15 only.

beaches.name: Manchester State Park
beaches.notes: Historic torpedo warehouse. Close to Manchester boat launch.

beaches.name: Blake Island State Park
beaches.notes: BOAT ACCESS ONLY. Open year-round. Marina area CLOSED. Views of Seattle skyline. Make clam chowder on beach!

beaches.name: Saltwater State Park
beaches.notes: Urban beach between Seattle and Tacoma. Good for beginners. Underwater park for divers.

beaches.name: Tolmie State Park
beaches.notes: Planted oyster bed - excellent for oysters. Not much clam resource. Day use only. 8 miles NE of Olympia.

beaches.name: Joemma Beach State Park
beaches.notes: Key Peninsula - formerly Robert Kennedy Recreation Area. Boat moorage available. Good oyster habitat.

beaches.name: Kayak Point County Park
beaches.notes: Popular beach park. Pier for fishing. Campground and day use areas.

beaches.name: Meadowdale County Park
beaches.notes: 1.25-mile trail to beach. Lunds Gulch Creek estuary. Day use only.

beaches.name: Mukilteo State Park
beaches.notes: Historic lighthouse. Near Whidbey Island ferry terminal. Scuba diving popular.

beaches.name: Larrabee State Park
beaches.notes: Washington's first state park. Rocky tide pools with mussels. Samish Bay views.

beaches.name: Shine Tidelands State Park
beaches.notes: GEODUCK beach! Excellent Manila/littleneck digging. 5,000ft of shoreline. Near Hood Canal Bridge. No restrooms.

beaches.name: Wolfe Property State Park
beaches.notes: Better oysters than Shine Tidelands. Adjacent to Shine. Walk/picnic along high tide line.

beaches.name: Triton Cove State Park
beaches.notes: Hood Canal location with good shellfish habitat. Small park, less crowded.

beaches.name: Pleasant Harbor State Park
beaches.notes: Sheltered harbor near Black Point. Excellent oyster habitat. Marina and resort nearby.

beaches.name: Point Whitney Tidelands
beaches.notes: Near WDFW shellfish hatchery. Oysters in lagoon and outer tidelands. 2.5in minimum oyster size.

beaches.name: Quilcene Bay
beaches.notes: Large Manila clam population. Famous Quilcene oysters - briny, light and clean flavor.

beaches.name: Discovery Park
beaches.notes: Seattle's largest park. CHECK CLOSURES - often closed due to urban runoff. West Point Lighthouse.

beaches.name: Lincoln Park
beaches.notes: West Seattle park with Colman Pool. Beach access. CHECK CLOSURES for urban beach status.

beaches.name: Seahurst County Park
beaches.notes: Burien beach park. Recently restored with seawall removal. Check biotoxin status.

beaches.name: Richmond Beach Saltwater Park
beaches.notes: Shoreline park. Sandy beach with tide flats. Rail tracks between parking and beach.

beaches.name: Fay Bainbridge Park
beaches.notes: Bainbridge Island park with camping. Views of Seattle skyline and Mt. Rainier.

beaches.name: Illahee State Park
beaches.notes: Near Bremerton. Pier for fishing. Old-growth forest trails. Camping available.

beaches.name: Kitsap Memorial State Park
beaches.notes: Northern Hood Canal. WWII memorial park. Good shellfish habitat in protected cove.

beaches.name: Foulweather Bluff (DNR-64)
beaches.notes: DNR public beach at Hood Canal-Admiralty junction. Nature Conservancy preserve nearby. Excellent views.

beaches.name: Cama Beach State Park
beaches.notes: Historic 1930s fishing resort on Camano Island. Restored cabins for rent. Saratoga Passage.

beaches.name: Fort Casey State Park
beaches.notes: Historic fort location. Good beach access with parking. Mix of sand and gravel.

beaches.name: South Whidbey State Park
beaches.notes: Beautiful old-growth forest backdrop. Beach access via trail.

beaches.name: Double Bluff State Park
beaches.notes: Popular off-leash dog beach. 2-mile beach with good clam habitat. Views of Olympics. Sandy flats good for horse clams.

beaches.name: Hope Island State Park
beaches.notes: GEODUCK beach! Popular geoduck spot on west/south sides. Boat access only. Watch for rough piddocks (split siphon).

beaches.name: Jarrell Cove State Park
beaches.notes: Protected cove with dock. Good for kayak/boat access.

beaches.name: McMicken Island State Park
beaches.notes: Island park connected to Harstene Island at low tide. Boat access recommended.

beaches.name: Oakland Bay
beaches.notes: Near Shelton - commercial oyster growing area. Taylor Shellfish nearby. Excellent oyster habitat.

beaches.name: Cutts Island State Park
beaches.notes: Small island in Carr Inlet. BOAT ACCESS ONLY - kayak/paddleboard accessible. Undeveloped marine park.

beaches.name: Burfoot County Park
beaches.notes: Budd Inlet beach near Boston Harbor. Old-growth forest trail. Quiet alternative to Tolmie.

beaches.name: Frye Cove County Park
beaches.notes: GEODUCK beach! Good variety of shellfish. Near Olympia.

beaches.name: Spencer Spit State Park
beaches.notes: Lopez Island - car accessible! Best clams on north side of spit in muddy gravel. Lagoon CLOSED.

beaches.name: Odlin County Park
beaches.notes: Alternative to Spencer Spit on Lopez Island. Near ferry landing.

beaches.name: West Penn Cove
beaches.notes: Penn Cove mussel country! Penn Cove Shellfish operates commercial mussel rafts here. World-famous mussels.

beaches.name: Picnic Point County Park
beaches.notes: Sandy beach with pier. Stream flows through. Popular swimming beach in summer.

beaches.name: Howarth Park
beaches.notes: Everett city park. Pedestrian bridge over railroad tracks to beach. Playground and trails.

beaches.name: Duckabush
beaches.notes: GEODUCK beach! Top spot to watch experienced geoduck diggers. Great Manila bed. Less crowded than Dosewallips. Open year-round.

beaches.name: Possession Point State Park
beaches.notes: Southern tip of Whidbey Island. Sandy beach with good clam habitat. Views of Seattle.

beaches.name: Freeland County Park
beaches.notes: Holmes Harbor area. Protected bay with boat launch. Family-friendly beach.

beaches.name: Dave Mackie County Park
beaches.notes: Sandy Point area on south Whidbey. Good beach access.

beaches.name: Useless Bay (South)
beaches.notes: Large tide flats - excellent for clamming. Near Double Bluff. Sandy substrate with horse clams.

beaches.name: Scatchet Head
beaches.notes: Bluff area with beach access. More rocky substrate.

beaches.name: Mutiny Bay
beaches.notes: Protected bay with good shellfish habitat.

beaches.name: Lagoon Point
beaches.notes: Private community area - check access. Near Greenbank.

beaches.name: Bush Point
beaches.notes: Historic lighthouse area. Narrow passage with strong currents.

beaches.name: Coupeville
beaches.notes: Penn Cove - famous for world-class mussels! Penn Cove Shellfish farm nearby. Best mussels Oct-April.

beaches.name: Oak Harbor Beach
beaches.notes: City beach near downtown Oak Harbor. Naval Air Station nearby.

beaches.name: Deception Pass State Park
beaches.notes: Scenic bridge and park. Rocky shoreline in places. Strong currents.

beaches.name: Joseph Whidbey State Park
beaches.notes: West-facing beach on Strait of Juan de Fuca. Can be windy.

beaches.name: Libbey Beach County Park
beaches.notes: Near Fort Ebey. Long sandy beach good for families.

beaches.name: Fort Ebey State Park
beaches.notes: WWII-era fort. Hiking trails and campground. Mixed sand/gravel beach.

beaches.name: Point Robinson
beaches.notes: One of the best Vashon beaches! Historic lighthouse. Large sandy tide flats. Excellent Manila clams.

beaches.name: Lisabeula Park
beaches.notes: West side of Vashon. Quiet beach with good clam habitat. Limited parking.

beaches.name: Dockton County Park
beaches.notes: Maury Island side near Quartermaster Harbor. CHECK STATUS - often closed due to biotoxin. Boat launch available.

beaches.name: KVI Beach
beaches.notes: North end of Vashon near ferry terminal. Named after old radio tower. Sandy beach.

beaches.name: Burton Acres Park
beaches.notes: Jensen Point area on Quartermaster Harbor. Protected bay with calm waters. Good for families.

beaches.name: Tramp Harbor
beaches.notes: East side of Vashon/Maury Island. Public fishing pier. Good clam flats at low tide.

beaches.name: DNR-77 (Vashon Island)
beaches.notes: BOAT ACCESS ONLY - no public upland access. West side of Vashon on Colvos Passage. Open year-round.

beaches.name: DNR-78 (Vashon Island)
beaches.notes: BOAT ACCESS ONLY - no public upland access. West side of Vashon on Colvos Passage. Open year-round.

beaches.name: DNR-79 (Vashon Island)
beaches.notes: BOAT ACCESS ONLY - no public upland access. West side of Vashon. Open year-round.

beaches.name: DNR-83 (Vashon Island)
beaches.notes: BOAT ACCESS ONLY - no public upland access. East side of Maury Island. Open year-round.

beaches.name: DNR-85 (Vashon Island)
beaches.notes: BOAT ACCESS ONLY - no public upland access. Southeast side of Maury Island. Open year-round.

beaches.name: North End Boat Ramp (Vashon)
beaches.notes: North tip of Vashon near ferry terminal. Water access for shellfish. Open year-round.

beaches.name: Fern Cove
beaches.notes: Nature preserve at Shinglemill Creek delta. Limited access - check preserve rules. Northwest Vashon.
